##South China Seafood Market "latent" of a family of four were quarantined, the lead "Laogu" found

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to clear the fog, to seek the truth, to watch the Times.

The man in his 60s in the family of four is

Gu Gangsheng, a former manager of the market

The merchants used to call him "the patron. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The South China Seafood Market was closed on January 1,2020. (photo by Danni Peng, staff writer)

On March 3, Wuhan Police, Disease Control and other department staff in the south China Seafood Market for a new round of disinfection process, found a family of four have been living in the market during the epidemic. The family of four, "a couple with an old man and child, " lived in the seafood market for 43 days without protection and were not found to be infected, Hubei Satellite TV reported. When the family's story came to light, it was high-profile.

Several vendors operating in the south China seafood market confirmed to China News weekly that the man in his 60s was Gu Gangsheng, a former manager of the market, known as "Lao Gu" by the vendors. The dormitory where his family lived during the outbreak is located on the second floor of the Eastern District of the south China Seafood Market.

On the afternoon of March 14, China Newsweek contacted Gu by telephone, and he confirmed that he was indeed one of the family of four mentioned in the news report as living in the south China seafood market. In addition to him, "the other three are my Godson, goddaughter-in-law and Godgrandson. "

The operator of "Yang Zhihui hairy crabs" at the south China Seafood Market said that after a new round of virus disinfection on March 3, businesses in the market were worried about the safety of their shops' properties, many people in the market wechat group to Gu gangsheng consulting about the situation. A few days later, Gu gangsheng replied in the Wechat Group, "the market is now cleared up, and I am out. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
After the south China seafood market was accused of being the source of the new coronavirus infection, there were five managers left, four of whom worked in the market office during the day and returned home at night, while Gu gangsheng lived in a dormitory at the South China Seafood Market for years, so basically 24 hours in the market, after the official outbreak, has been living here, until March 3 was found.

After the south China Seafood Market was shut down on January 1, the "Yang Zhihui hairy crab" operator had met Gu gangsheng three times. The first was on the afternoon of January 1, the day the market was seized, when he saw Gu gangsheng answering a question from a merchant. "The situation has clarified that the market will open, " Gu said. The other two meetings took place before the city was sealed off in Wuhan, he went to ask when the market would reopen, and Gu was there to calm the merchants.

According to the operator, he met Gu Gangsheng in 2002 when the south China Seafood Market was first established. According to public information, the south China Seafood Market was officially established in 2005. But according to media reports, the seafood market has been around since 1990s, only registering as a management company in 2005. At the time, Gu was deputy general manager of the South China Seafood Market. Later, when he reached retirement age, the merchants in the market did not know Gu's specific position, only that he was still involved in the management of the market, in charge of collecting rents, inspecting hygiene, coordinating disputes and so on.

According to reports, Gu gangsheng started living in a dormitory at the south China Seafood Market around 2012. He lived in Beixin village, a village in the city near the market. Station north new village after demolition, he moved to the market dormitory.

Gu's Godson is a rice seller in the market, according to people familiar with the matter interviewed by the upstream news. In addition, the source said Gu had a bad relationship with his wife and his son had died.

"Every family has its own problems, " Gu said in an interview with China News weekly, referring to rumors about his personal family. "I hope we don't listen to rumors about personal matters. " For more details, he declined to discuss it further.

The South China seafood market is the largest seafood wholesale market in central China, with about 50,000 square meters and more than 1,000 households, according to the Gross leasable area. As the manager of the Seafood Market, why does Gu Gangsheng live in the market dormitory? Market managers may not be as well paid as outsiders think. According to a businessman surnamed Tan in the Red Star News interview market, Gu usually earns 4,000 to 5,000 yuan a month. After deducting social security, most of his salary is spent on living expenses.

The family of four was sent to a hotel in Wuhan to be quarantined, Hubei Satellite TV reported on March 3.
